<DOC><DOCNO> AP900509-0277 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-90 2124EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-TobaccoResolution     05-09 0206</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Tobacco Resolution,0215</SECOND><HEAD>American Brands Defeats Anti-Tobacco Proposal</HEAD><DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Shareholders of American Brands Inc.,which makes Carlton, Lucky Strike, Pall Mall, Tareyton and othercigarettes, rejected a proposal to dump the company's tobaccobusinesses.   But the resolution, which asked the company to stop producingand marketing tobacco by the year 2000, received enough votes to beraised again at next year's meeting. Nearly 4 percent ofstockholders backed the resolution.   In addition to making cigarettes, American Brands sells liquor,life insurance, office products, golf supplies, hardware andhousewares.   ``I'm encouraged. We'll submit it again next year,'' said JeannePinard, a Massachusetts teacher who introduced the proposal.   American Brands Chairman William J. Alley told the meeting inNew York on Tuesday that tobacco products represent an importantsegment of the company's business, and earnings have been asignificant source of revenues.   ``Smoking is a matter of choice for each individual,'' he said,answering a question.   Alley refused to comment on tobacco-related health risks becauseof pending litigation. He said the company is involved in 41 of the67 pending cases against the tobacco industry.   He criticized the government for trying to impose newrestrictions on the industry, such as bans on tobaccoadvertisements.</TEXT></DOC>